# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alfred-newton-richards
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz was born in Neuchâtel, Switzerland, and immigrated to the United States in 1849, joining his father Louis Agassiz, after his mother Cecile (Braun) Agassiz died in 1848.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Thereupon, his father enrolled him in the Cambridge High School, before entering Harvard at the age of 15.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] He graduated from Harvard University in 1855, subsequently studying engineering and chemistry, and taking the degree of Bachelor of Science at the Lawrence Scientific School of the same institution in 1857; in 1859 became an assistant in the United States Coast Survey, onboard the Fauntleroy.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] In 1860, he became an agent for the Museum of Comparative Zoology, and married Anna Russell.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Thenceforward he became a specialist in marine ichthyology.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz was elected a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1862.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Up until the summer of 1866, Agassiz worked as assistant curator in the museum of natural history that his father founded at Harvard.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Hulbert persuaded Agassiz's brother-in-law, Quincy Adams Shaw, and friends to invest in a rich copper lode discovered on Michigan's Keweenaw Peninsula, called the Calumet Mine.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] In 1866, Agassiz visited the outcrop and noted that the Calumet Conglomerate was a porphyry almost fourteen feet wide, dipping to the northwest at a 35 degree angle.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] The rich nature of the deposit convinced Shaw to purchase the land to the south, forming the Hecla Mining Company.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz was then made treasurer of both companies.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Disappointed in Hulbert's management of the Calumet, Agassiz replaced Hulbert with a new manager called Davis in December.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz states, "I have put in every cent of mine into these two mines." Convinced the deposit could be developed at a profit, Agassiz was made superintendent of both mines, and arrived on site in March 1867.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] By September 1868, Hecla was producing 185 tons of ingot, the Calumet 140, and both mills stamping 4000 tons of rock per month.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz was able to place George Hardie in charge, and returned to Cambridge in October.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz continued to visit the mines every spring and fall.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] In December 1869, the Hecla paid its first dividend, and the Calumet did so in August 1870.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] In May 1871, the Calumet and Hecla Mining Company was formed after consolidating with the Portland and Scott Mining Companies.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Shaw was the first president, but soon retired to the board of directors, when Agassiz assumed the presidency until his death.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] In 1883, Agassiz innovated by installing a giant engine, known as the Superior, which was able to lift 24 tons of rock from a depth of 1,200 metres (3,900 feet).
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] He also built a railroad and dredged a channel to navigable waters.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] With Erasmus Darwin Leavitt Jr. employed as his mechanical engineer, Agassiz installed state of the art hoisting engines.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Out of his copper fortune, he gave some US$500,000 to Harvard for the museum of comparative zoology and other purposes.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] In 1875, Agassiz built a marine laboratory on his summer estate located at Castle Hill, Newport, Rhode Island, hoping to carry on the work his father started at Penikese Island.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] In 1877, Agassiz opened the Newport Marine Zoological Laboratory.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz hosted grad students there until 1897, and continued to use the lab until his death.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] He assisted Charles Wyville Thomson in the examination and classification of the collections of the 1872 *Challenger* Expedition, and wrote the *Review of the Echini* (2 vols., 1872–1874) in the reports.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Between 1877 and 1880, he took part in the three dredging expeditions of the steamer *Blake* of the Coast Survey (renamed the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey in 1878), and presented a full account of them in two volumes (1888).
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Also in 1875, he was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] In 1896, Agassiz visited Fiji and Queensland and inspected the Great Barrier Reef, publishing a paper on the subject in 1898.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Of Agassiz's other writings on marine zoology, most are contained in the bulletins and memoirs of the museum of comparative zoology.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] However, in 1865, he published with Elizabeth Cary Agassiz, his stepmother, *Seaside Studies in Natural History*, a work at once exact and stimulating.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] They also published, in 1871, *Marine Animals of Massachusetts Bay*.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] He received the German Order Pour le Mérite for Science and Arts in August 1902.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz also received the Victoria Research Medal, and the Legion of Honour.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Agassiz served as a president of the National Academy of Sciences, which since 1913 has awarded the Alexander Agassiz Medal in his memory.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] He died in 1910 on board the RMS *Adriatic* en route to New York from Southampton.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] He and his wife Anna Russell (1840–1873) were the parents of three sons – George Russell Agassiz (1861–1951), Maximilian Agassiz (1866–1943) and Rodolphe Louis Agassiz (1871–1933).
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] Alexander Agassiz is commemorated in the scientific name of a species of lizard, *Anolis agassizi*, and a fish, *Leptochilichthys agassizii*.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] A statue of Alexander Agassiz erected in 1923 is located in Calumet, Michigan, next to his summer home where he stayed while fulfilling his duties as president of the Calumet and Hecla Mining Company.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] The Company Headquarters, Agassiz' statue, and many other buildings and landmarks from the now defunct company are administered and maintained by the Keweenaw National Historical Park, whose headquarters overlook the statue of Agassiz.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] A major building of the Hopkins Marine Station is named after him.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-agassiz] The RV (research vessel) Agassiz is named after him.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache was born in Philadelphia, the son of Richard Bache, Jr., and Sophia Burrell Dallas Bache.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] He came from a family prominent in American politics.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] He was the nephew of Vice-President George M.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Dallas, the grandson of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Dallas, and the great-grandson of Benjamin Franklin.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] After graduating from the United States Military Academy at West Point in 1825, as first in his class, he was an assistant professor of engineering there for some time.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] As a second lieutenant in the United States Army Corps of Engineers, he was engaged in the construction of Fort Adams in Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache resigned from the Army on June 1, 1829.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache was a professor of natural philosophy and chemistry at the University of Pennsylvania from 1828 to 1841 and again from 1842 to 1843.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] He spent 1836–1838 in Europe on behalf of the trustees of what became Girard College; he was named president of the college after his return.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Abroad, he examined European education systems, and on his return he published a valuable report.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] From 1839 to 1842, he served as the first president of Central High School of Philadelphia, one of the oldest public high schools in the United States.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1843, on the death of Professor Ferdinand Rudolph Hassler, Bache was appointed superintendent of the United States Coast Survey.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Whereas Hassler had faced continual doubts from Congress, Bache succeeded in convincing legislators of the value of geodesy in addition to geomagnetic and meteorological research.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] With many contacts, friends, and family among the nation's political and military leaders, Bache won liberal appropriations to build up his agency and greatly expand its work.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] By the mid 1850s it had become the federal government's leading scientific bureau.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1849, it began study of the Pacific Coast, which the US had newly acquired via the US-Mexico War and Oregon Treaty.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Assisted by Isaac Stevens, his number two in Washington, DC, Bache reorganized the Coast Survey so that it could complete initial mapping of the entire US coast.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] By the 1840s, a clique of leading US scientists began to coalesce around Bache with the goal of professionalizing their fields.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] They formalized with establishment of the Association of American Geologists and Naturalists in 1843 (renamed the American Association for the Advancement of Science five years later) and the Smithsonian Institution in 1846.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Informally, Bache and his circle called themselves the Scientific Lazzaroni.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Together, the groups created and enforced standards of intellectual merit with the goal of elevating the nation and its reputation.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] This meant discrediting charlatans but, at times, also denying research funding or academic appointments to others.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Perhaps most important, the groups advised and even mentored politicians and army engineers.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache would lead the AAAS until 1851 and serve on the Smithsonian's board of regents throughout his term as Coast Survey superintendent.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1863, amid the demands of the Civil War, Bache was a central figure in the establishment of the National Academy of Sciences, created by an act of Congress to provide scientific advice to the federal government.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] He was elected its first president and served in that role until his death in 1867.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] As the sectional crisis worsened through the late 1850s, Coast Survey budgets became ensnared by polarization and conflicts in Congress.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Then, the start of war in 1861 brought a stop to work along the South's Atlantic and Gulf coasts.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache withdrew Survey ships from the region so they would not fall into secessionists' hands.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] At the same time, some staff resigned to join the Confederacy.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] A number of trusted friends and Democratic allies, including senators Jefferson Davis and Stephen Mallory, would lead the rebellion — acts that Bache took as both political and personal treachery.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Yet the Civil War enhanced the Coast Survey's stature in Washington, D.C.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] By this time, the agency had amassed charts of southern harbors, rivers, and coastal terrain.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] The research gave a critical advantage to the Union navy and army.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Meanwhile, Bache continued to lead scientists to greater influence in government, helping to establish the U.S.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] He also played a central role in the founding of the National Academy of Sciences in 1863 and served as its first president.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] Official duties and private worries contributed to Bache's declining health.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] By 1864 he had suffered a stroke, which left him handicapped and unable to work without his wife's assistance.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] At the time of his death, he had served as head of the Coast Survey for 24 years.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] After the Civil War, Bache was elected a 3rd Class Companion of the Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States (MOLLUS) in consideration of his contributions to the war effort.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] He married Nancy Clark Fowler on September 30, 1838, in Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] She was born in Newport and died on January 13, 1870, in Philadelphia.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] She assisted in the publication of much of his work.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] They adopted one son, Henry Wood Bache (1839–1878).
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] He died at Newport, Rhode Island on February 17, 1867, from cerebral softening.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alexander-dallas-bache] He was buried in the Congressional Cemetery in Washington, D.C., under a monument designed by architect Henry Hobson Richardson.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alfred-newton-richards] Richards was born in Stamford, New York the son of Rev.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alfred-newton-richards] Richards and his wife, Mary Elizabeth Burbank.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alfred-newton-richards] He was educated at the Stamford Seminary and Union Free School.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alfred-newton-richards] He served as chairman of the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine's department of pharmacology from 1910 to 1946 and was the university's vice president of medical affairs from 1939 to 1948.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alfred-newton-richards] President Franklin Delano Roosevelt appointed Richards chairman of the Committee on Medical Research.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alfred-newton-richards] The office was terminated five years later, in 1946, after which Richards became president of the National Academy of Sciences, serving until 1950.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alfred-newton-richards] Richards' technique for the study of kidney functioning is considered a landmark in animal physiology research.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/alfred-newton-richards] The Richards Medical Research Laboratories building at the University of Pennsylvania, one of the best-known and most influential designs of architect Louis Kahn, is named for him.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The **American Academy of Arts and Sciences** (**The Academy**) is one of the oldest learned societies in the United States.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It was founded in 1780 during the American Revolution by John Adams, John Hancock, James Bowdoin, Andrew Oliver, and other Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Membership in the academy is achieved through a nominating petition, review, and election process.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy's quarterly journal, *Dædalus*, is published by the MIT Press on behalf of the academy, and has been open-access since January 2021.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy also conducts multidisciplinary public policy research.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Patton has served as President of the Academy since January 2025.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The first class of new members, chosen by the Academy in 1781, included Benjamin Franklin and George Washington as well as several international honorary members.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The initial volume of Academy *Memoirs* appeared in 1785, and the *Proceedings* followed in 1846.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the 1950s, the Academy launched its journal *Daedalus*, reflecting its commitment to a broader intellectual and socially-oriented program.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Since the second half of the twentieth century, independent research has become a central focus of the Academy.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1950s, arms control emerged as one of its signature concerns.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy also served as the catalyst in establishing the National Humanities Center in North Carolina.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1990s, the Academy developed a new strategic plan, focusing on four major areas: science, technology, and global security; social policy and education; humanities and culture; and education.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In 2002, the Academy established a visiting scholars program in association with Harvard University.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] More than 75 academic institutions from across the country have become Affiliates of the Academy to support this program and other Academy initiatives.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy has sponsored a number of awards and prizes, throughout its history and has offered opportunities for fellowships and visiting scholars at the Academy.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In July 2013, *The Boston Globe* exposed then president Leslie Berlowitz for falsifying her credentials, faking a doctorate, and consistently mistreating her staff.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is modeled on the Science and Engineering Indicators, published biennially by the National Science Board as required by Congress.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Ever since the founding of the Academy, its members have been nominated and elected by peers.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Members of the Academy included not only scientists and scholars, but also writers and artists as well as representatives from the full range of professions and public life.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Throughout the Academy's history, more than 10,000 fellows have been elected.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Astronomer Maria Mitchell was the first woman elected to the Academy, in 1848.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The current membership encompasses over 5,700 members based across the United States and around the world.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Academy members include more than 250 Nobel laureates and more than 60 Pulitzer Prize winners.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Of the Academy's 14,343 members since 1780, 1,406 are or have been affiliated with Harvard University, 611 with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 433 with Yale University, 425 with the University of California, Berkeley, and 404 with Stanford University.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The following table includes those institutions affiliated with 300 or more members.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] † Excludes members affiliated exclusively with associated national laboratories.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] As of 2023, membership is divided into five classes and thirty specialties.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The **Association of American Medical Colleges** (**AAMC**) is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization based in Washington, D.C. that was established in June 1876.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] It represents medical schools, teaching hospitals, and academic and scientific societies, while providing services to its member institutions that include data from medical, education, and health studies, as well as consulting.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The AAMC administers the Medical College Admission Test and operates the American Medical College Application Service and the Electronic Residency Application Service.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Along with the American Medical Association (AMA), the AAMC co-sponsors the Liaison Committee on Medical Education (LCME), the accrediting body for all U.S.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The AAMC was founded in 1876 at Jefferson Medical College in Philadelphia to establish standards for member medical schools.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The first meeting was held on June 2, 1876, and included members from 22 medical colleges.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Jefferson Medical College's Dean, John B.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Biddle, was the first president of the Association.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] By 1905, the Association expanded its standards to require member schools to offer a four-year medical curriculum of no less than 4,000 hours.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] In 1942, the AAMC partnered with the American Medical Association's (AMA) Council on Medical Education and Hospitals to form the Liaison Committee on Medical Education (LCME).
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The LCME is an accrediting agency for educational programs at medical schools in the United States and Canada.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Kirch became president and CEO of AAMC, he served until 2019.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Skorton replaced Kirch as president and CEO.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] In 2015, the AAMC announced MCAT examinees with documented disabilities would no longer be required to inform schools if they received accommodations during their exam.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Prior to this, if someone received accommodations due to a documented disability, an asterisk was affixed to the score report to inform all schools the individual applied to.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The schools were not informed of the specific disability or nature of the accommodations.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020, the AAMC created a database of treatment and management guidance for clinicians.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The resources are divided into various topics, including infection control, emergency department, inpatient, ambulatory, serious illness communication, mental health, and special populations.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The AAMC also recommended that medical schools temporarily suspend medical students' direct patient contact due to safety concerns.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Throughout 2020, the AAMC was criticized for continuing to hold the MCAT exam in person during the COVID pandemic.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] In October 2020, the Association responded to lawmaker's concerns over in-person testing by saying it had resumed only when safety protocols had been developed and implemented.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] In 2020, the AAMC removed Abraham Flexner's name from their annual award, claiming his 1910 report contained "racist and sexist" statements.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] This claim, however, has been challenged.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The Association is a nonprofit organization that represents medical schools, teaching hospitals, and academic and scientific societies.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] All accredited MD-granting medical schools in the United States and Canada are members of the AAMC.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Membership also includes teaching hospitals or health systems, including 51 Department of Veterans Affairs medical centers, and academic societies are also members.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The AAMC provides services including data from medical, education, and health studies, as well as consulting.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The organization hosts events each year that offer continuing medical education and professional development to the health workforce.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The Association is governed by a 17-member board of directors.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Ten of the board members are the chairs of the Association's three member councils: the Council of Deans, the Council of Teaching Hospitals and Health Systems, and the Council of Faculty and Academic Societies.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The remaining 7 include a medical student, a resident physician, and a member of the public not affiliated with the AAMC, a medical school, or a teaching hospital.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The Council of Faculty and Academic Societies has 94 member professional organizations.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Members consist of faculty from U.S. medical schools and teaching hospitals.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The Council of Teaching Hospitals and Health Systems is composed of around 400 teaching hospitals, including Veteran Affairs medical centers.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The Council of Deans is composed of deans from all accredited medical schools in the U.S. and 17 Canadian schools.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] In January 2022, the Association of American Medical Colleges and the Association of Academic Health Centers (AAHC) approved a merger agreement.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Under the agreement, the AAHC joined the AAMC on April 1, 2022, according to a Jan.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The AAHC was founded in 1969 and lists over 120 U.S. and international member organizations on its website.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The latter are part of the Association of Academic Health Centers International (AAHCI), a subsidiary of the U.S. organization founded in 2008.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The AAMC administers the Medical College Admission Test and operates the American Medical College Application Service and the Electronic Residency Application Service, which facilitate students applying to medical schools and residency programs.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The MCAT was formed in 1928 and was known as the "Scholastic Aptitude Test for Medical Students".
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] In 1948, it was renamed the "Medical College Admission Test".
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] In 2015, after a review process, a new version of the test was introduced by the AAMC.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The new exam added a Psychological, Social, and Biological Foundations of Behavior section.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The review for the new exam was led by a 21-member committee composed by the Association and called the MR5 Committee.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The MR5 Committee consisted of medical school deans; admissions, educational affairs, student affairs, and diversity officers; basic science and clinical faculty; pre-health advisors and undergraduate faculty; and a medical student and a physician resident.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The MR5 Committee also reached out to subcommittees of experts in fields such as psychology, sociology, and anthropology.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The Association maintains a "What's on the MCAT Exam?" webpage that includes a comprehensive list of all tested topics.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] They also offer a Fee Assistance Program for test takers who require financial aid in order to take the MCAT.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Led by the AAMC, the American Medical College Application Service (AMCAS) administers and processes medical school applications.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Most U.S. medical schools participate in the AMCAS.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] AMCAS was first used by applicants to medical schools in 1969.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The AAMC developed the Electronic Residency Application Service (ERAS) to allow final-year medical school students and graduates to apply electronically for residency positions.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The Association conducts studies, research, and publications on medical education, health care, and biomedical research and provides publications and forums to support medical education and educational health programs.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The AAMC published a three-part report on conflicts of interest in research and medical education settings.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The final report was titled "In the Interest of Patients: Recommendations for Physician Financial Relationships and Clinical Decision Making," and was released in 2010.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] The AAMC publishes the peer-reviewed journal *Academic Medicine*.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-medical-colleges] Past papers of the association are held at the National Library of Medicine.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] Election to the AAP is an honor extended to individuals with outstanding credentials in biomedical science and/or translational biomedical research and is limited to 60 persons per year.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] The AAP includes about 1000 active members and 550 emeritus and honorary members.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] However, other countries are also represented.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] The range of topics studied by members of the AAP is as broad as medicine itself, ranging from fundamental biological questions to translational research (development and testing of new treatments) to public policy issues.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] The "Transactions of the Association of American Physicians," published until 1995, recorded the presentations of members at the annual meeting.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] In that year, it was replaced by the bimonthly "Proceedings of the Association of American Physicians" (no longer published).
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] The AAP honors selected scientists with the George M.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] Kober Medal (started in 1927; awarded annually since 1929, except for 1944 and 1946) and the George M.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] Kober Lectureship (awarded every three years since 1925), for outstanding contributions to medicine or medical science.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] The AAP holds a joint meeting each year with the American Society for Clinical Investigation (ASCI), another honorary medical society with closely related goals.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] Some of the most important advances in biomedical science were first reported at annual AAP meetings.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] These included the discovery of insulin by Banting and Macleod in 1922, and discovery, by Minot and Murphy in 1926, that pernicious anemia could be treated by feeding patients extracts of raw liver.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] Members of the AAP have included Nobel laureates, and members of the United States National Academy of Sciences and the Institute of Medicine.
[src:alfred-newton-richards/association-of-american-physicians] Living members of the AAP who have also been awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine include Barry Marshall, Stanley Prusiner, Michael S.
